

⸻

Component: SignalDrawer

Purpose:
Allow deep exploration of a single Signal Pile without polluting the main Signal View.

Mental model:
Surface = Radar
Drawer = Microscope

⸻

1️⃣ Trigger Behavior

Interaction
	•	Click anywhere on a SignalPile (pas sur un sous-élément spécifique)
	•	Drawer slides from right
	•	Background content remains visible but dimmed (existing overlay token)
	•	Selected pile stays visually highlighted

⸻

2️⃣ Layout Structure

|---------------- Main View ---------------|   |----- Drawer -----|
                                                  Header
                                                  Tab Selector
                                                  Content Area
                                                  Evidence Block

Width:
	•	40%–45% viewport desktop
	•	Fullscreen on mobile
	•	Max-width cap (ex: 720px) pour éviter lignes trop longues

⸻

3️⃣ Drawer Header

A. Signal Title

Same as pile title.
Use existing H2 or H3 large style.

Example:
Listing Initiation Friction

Under it (meta row):
	•	Signal strength badge
	•	Affected feature tag
	•	Convergence count

Same design tokens as main view.

Spacing:
16px bottom before tabs.

⸻

4️⃣ Tab Selector (Core Interaction)

Position:
Directly under header.

Style:
Use existing segmented control or tab component.

Tabs:
	•	Problem
	•	Impact
	•	Cause
	•	Realignment

Rules:
	•	Only one active at a time
	•	Active tab uses system primary state
	•	Others neutral

Interaction:
	•	Click tab → content animates (slide transition)
	•	Swipe right/left (trackpad or mobile) → navigates between tabs
	•	Keep animation subtle (200–300ms max)
	•	Directional slide:
	•	Going right → content slides left
	•	Going left → content slides right

This reinforces the pathway logic.

⸻

5️⃣ Content Area

This is the core reading area.

Layout:
Single column.
Generous padding (24–32px).
Max readable line width (60–75 characters).

⸻

Each Tab Content Structure

A. Section Label (small overline)

Example:
PROBLEM

Use existing label/overline typography.

⸻

B. Main Text Block

This is the expanded RITE text.
No truncation here.

Max:
	•	3–6 sentences
	•	Avoid long academic paragraphs

This should feel strategic, not verbose.

⸻

C. Optional Structured Sub-blocks

Depending on tab:

If Problem:
	•	User expectation (short line)
	•	Observed behavior (short line)

If Impact:
	•	Affected feature
	•	Business risk (qualitative)

If Cause:
	•	UI factor
	•	Structural factor

If Realignment:
	•	Proposed direction
	•	Implementation level (UI / structural / strategic)

Keep them minimal.

⸻

6️⃣ Evidence Block (Below Main Content)

Divider line (existing subtle border token).

Title:
Supporting Evidence

Contains:
	•	Timestamps (clickable)
	•	Short quotes
	•	Link to video jump (if available)

Each evidence item:
Small card or row format.

Example:

[4:57]
“I don’t see where to list an item…”

Clickable → jumps to that timestamp.

This reinforces trust.

⸻

7️⃣ Navigation UX Details

Keyboard Support
	•	Arrow Right → next tab
	•	Arrow Left → previous tab
	•	ESC → close drawer

Close Behavior
	•	Close icon top right
	•	Clicking overlay closes
	•	Preserve scroll position in main view

⸻

8️⃣ Visual Hierarchy Priorities

Inside drawer:
	1.	Signal title
	2.	Active tab content
	3.	Evidence

Do not:
	•	Overemphasize tags
	•	Add decorative UI
	•	Introduce new color accents

The drawer should feel calm and analytical.

⸻

9️⃣ State Persistence

If user switches tab → closes drawer → reopens same pile:

You can either:
	•	Reset to Problem (recommended for clarity)
OR
	•	Remember last tab state (advanced behavior)

I recommend reset to Problem for predictability.

⸻

10️⃣ Critical UX Principle

The drawer must:
	•	Feel like depth
	•	Not like another page
	•	Not like a report
	•	Not like documentation

It is a focused signal dissection.

One signal.
Four lenses.
Evidence below.

⸻

11️⃣ What This Achieves Strategically

Now your system becomes:

Main View → Where misalignment exists
Drawer → Why it exists and how to realign

You preserve:
	•	Signal compression
	•	Strategic readability
	•	Methodology integrity
	•	Product credibility

